(Visual: Page 2 content - What is GLPI? ITAM & ITSM)

"So, what exactly is GLPI? The name stands for Gestionnaire Libre de Parc Informatique. At its core, GLPI serves two critical functions:"

  • "Second, it is a robust IT Service Management (ITSM) and service desk solution. It manages incidents, problems, and changes in compliance with ITIL standards, ensuring efficient and structured IT support delivery."

(Visual: Page 3 content - Dashboard screenshot and Asset Management list)

  • "We also have robust tools for Software and Licenses management, ensuring license compliance and tracking expiration dates."

  • "Finally, it provides complete Lifecycle Management, monitoring an asset's status from procurement all the way to retirement."

(Visual: Page 4 content - Service Desk & Ticketing features)

  • "And critically, there's SLA & Analytics. You can define Service Level Agreements (SLAs), Operational Level Agreements (OLAs), and track performance metrics to ensure you meet your service commitments."

(Visual: Page 5 content - Architecture & Technology: PHP, Database, Agent)

  • "For the Database, it utilizes MySQL or MariaDB, providing robust data storage and ensuring scalability for both small businesses and large enterprises."

  • "Finally, the GLPI Agent. This is a Perl/C++ based agent that runs on Windows, Linux, and macOS, automating inventory collection and deployment tasks."

  • "It performs a Deep Inventory, collecting detailed hardware specifications like CPU, RAM, and serial numbers, as well as installed software."

  • "Beyond inventory, it can handle Task Execution, allowing you to remotely deploy software packages and run scripts."

what is tco

TCO stands for Total Cost of Ownership.

It is a financial estimate used by businesses and individuals to determine the complete, long-term cost of owning a product, system, or service over its entire lifecycle.

TCO goes far beyond the initial purchase price and includes both direct and indirect costs.

Key Components of TCO

The calculation of TCO typically includes:

  1. Acquisition/Initial Costs:

    • Purchase price or licensing fees.

    • Implementation, installation, and configuration costs.

    • Data migration expenses.

  2. Operating/Ongoing Costs:

    • Maintenance and repair costs.

    • Subscription fees (for cloud or SaaS solutions).

    • Energy consumption and infrastructure (e.g., floor space, electricity for servers).

    • Personnel costs (IT staff time for management and support).

  3. Indirect/Hidden Costs:

    • End-user training and education.

    • Downtime, service disruption, and recovery expenses.

    • Security risks and mitigation.

    • Future upgrade or replacement costs.

In the context of the GLPI overview you provided, the tool is highlighted as reducing TCO because, as an Open Source solution, it eliminates the high recurring licensing costs associated with proprietary software (like the "Per user/agent/month" fees of tools like Jira or ServiceNow).
